Goodyear Welt: A welt is a strip of leather
column26: or plastic that is stitched to the upper and insole of a shoe as an attach-point for the sole. The space enclosed by the welt is then filled with cork or some other filler material (usually either porous or perforated for breathability)
column27: and the outsole is both cemented and stitched to the welt. This process of making shoes is referred to as a Goodyear welt construction
column28: as the machinery used for the process was invented by Charles Goodyear

Jr. in 1869.
